- to be honest the concept of type juggling is still a bit confusing to me even in JS. especially the comparison operators, like == and ===, and how they behave differently when comparing different types of values. i understand that == does type coercion and can compare values of different types, while === does not do type coercion and only returns true if the values are of the same type and have the same value. but i still find it a bit tricky to remember which operator to use in different situations, especially when dealing with user input or data from external sources where the type might not be what i expect. i guess with more practice and experience, it will become more intuitive to know when to use == vs ===.
- another thing that i find a bit confusing is the concept of truthy and falsy values in PHP. i understand that in PHP, certain values are considered falsy, such as false, 0, 0.0, "", "0", null, and an empty array. but it can be a bit tricky to remember all the different falsy values and how they behave in different contexts, especially when using them in conditional statements or loops. i guess with more practice and experience, it will become more intuitive to understand which values are truthy and which are falsy in PHP.

- im not sure what to return in the function for task 2, im assuming it just return the args.

- FOLLOW UP: Ok i think i just missunderstood the concept of "type coercion". From what i can understand it some kind of type enforcement that happens when you compare two values of different types, where PHP will try to convert one of the values to the type of the other value in order to make the comparison work. so for example, when you compare a string "0" with an integer 0 using ==, PHP will convert the string "0" to an integer 0 before making the comparison, which is why it returns true. but when you use ===, it does not do any type coercion and simply compares the values as they are, which is why "0" === 0 returns false. so in a way, type coercion is like a behind-the-scenes process that happens during loose comparisons (==) where PHP tries to make sense of the different types and find a common ground for comparison.
- although im not really sure does the type coercion happens in one side of the comparison or both sides, like does PHP convert the string to an integer, or does it convert the integer to a string, or does it convert both values to some common type? i guess it might depend on the specific values being compared and the context of the comparison. but overall, i think the key takeaway is that type coercion is a process that happens during loose comparisons (==) where PHP tries to make sense of different types and find a way to compare them, which can lead to some surprising results if you're not careful.

